Structures of Authority
pasted-image.tiff
Domination is the likelihood that commands will be obeyed by a given group of persons.
Three bases on which authority is made legitimate to followers:
Rational: rests on a belief in the legality of rules and the right of those with authority to issue commands.
Traditional: the sanctity of traditions and the legitimacy of those exercising authority under them.
Charismatic: the devotion of followers to the special sanctity, exemplary character, heroism, or special powers of leaders.
